    "id": "pms_vs_pmdd",
    "title": "PMS vs PMDD",
    "category": "Period Health",
    "readTime": "8 min read",
    "summary": "Understand the difference between common PMS symptoms and the more severe condition known as PMDD.",
    "content": "# PMS vs PMDD\n\nMany people experience emotional and physical symptoms before their period.\n\nWhile PMS is common, some individuals experience a more severe condition called Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD).\n\nUnderstanding the difference can help you seek appropriate support.\n\n## What Is PMS?\n\nPremenstrual Syndrome (PMS) refers to symptoms that occur during the days or weeks before menstruation.\n\nCommon symptoms include:\n\n• Bloating\n• Breast tenderness\n• Mild mood changes\n• Food cravings\n• Fatigue\n• Headaches\n• Irritability\n\nSymptoms usually improve shortly after menstruation begins.\n\n## What Is PMDD?\n\nPremenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD) is a more severe form of premenstrual symptoms.\n\nPMDD can significantly affect daily life, relationships, work, and emotional wellbeing.\n\n## Common PMDD Symptoms\n\n• Severe mood swings\n• Intense sadness\n• Anxiety\n• Irritability\n• Difficulty concentrating\n• Feeling overwhelmed\n• Changes in sleep patterns\n• Extreme fatigue\n\nSymptoms often improve after menstruation starts.\n\n## Key Difference\n\nPMS may be uncomfortable but usually remains manageable.\n\nPMDD can seriously interfere with normal functioning and quality of life.\n\n## When To Seek Help\n\nConsider speaking with a healthcare professional if symptoms:\n\n• Affect school or work\n• Impact relationships\n• Cause severe emotional distress\n• Occur consistently each cycle\n\n## Self-Care Strategies\n\nHelpful habits may include:\n\n• Regular exercise\n• Adequate sleep\n• Stress management\n• Balanced nutrition\n• Tracking symptoms\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Severe premenstrual symptoms are just part of being a woman.\n\nFact: Symptoms that disrupt daily life deserve attention and support.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nPMS is common and usually mild to moderate. PMDD is a more severe condition that can significantly affect emotional and physical wellbeing. Tracking symptoms can help identify patterns and support diagnosis."
