    "id": "painful_periods_dysmenorrhea",
    "title": "Painful Periods (Dysmenorrhea)",
    "category": "Period Health",
    "readTime": "9 min read",
    "summary": "Understand why period cramps happen, what is considered normal, and when pain may need medical attention.",
    "content": "# Painful Periods (Dysmenorrhea)\n\nMany people experience cramps during menstruation.\n\nThis condition is known as dysmenorrhea.\n\nWhile mild to moderate cramps are common, severe pain that disrupts daily activities should not be ignored.\n\n## Why Do Period Cramps Happen?\n\nDuring menstruation, the uterus contracts to help shed its lining.\n\nThese contractions are triggered by substances called prostaglandins.\n\nHigher prostaglandin levels can lead to stronger contractions and more intense pain.\n\n## Common Symptoms\n\nSymptoms may include:\n\n• Cramping in the lower abdomen\n• Lower back pain\n• Nausea\n• Fatigue\n• Headaches\n• Diarrhea\n• Leg discomfort\n\n## Primary Dysmenorrhea\n\nPrimary dysmenorrhea refers to common menstrual cramps without an underlying medical condition.\n\nIt often begins during adolescence and may improve with age.\n\n## Secondary Dysmenorrhea\n\nSecondary dysmenorrhea occurs when another condition causes pain.\n\nPossible causes include:\n\n• Endometriosis\n• Fibroids\n• Pelvic inflammatory disease\n• Adenomyosis\n\n## Managing Period Pain\n\nMany people find relief through:\n\n• Heat therapy\n• Gentle exercise\n• Adequate sleep\n• Stress management\n• Staying hydrated\n\nA healthcare professional may recommend additional treatment options when needed.\n\n## When To Seek Medical Advice\n\nConsult a healthcare professional if:\n\n• Pain suddenly becomes worse\n• Pain prevents normal activities\n• Symptoms do not improve with usual measures\n• Heavy bleeding occurs alongside severe pain\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Severe period pain is something everyone must simply tolerate.\n\nFact: Severe or worsening pain may indicate an underlying condition and deserves medical evaluation.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nPeriod cramps are common, but severe pain should not be ignored. Understanding the cause of menstrual pain can help guide effective management and improve quality of life."
