    "content": "# First Trimester Pregnancy Guide\n\nThe first trimester covers weeks 1 through 12 of pregnancy.\n\nThis is a period of rapid growth and development for the baby and significant changes for the mother.\n\n## Baby's Development\n\nDuring the first trimester:\n\n• The brain begins developing\n• The heart starts beating\n• Major organs begin forming\n• Arms and legs develop\n• Facial features start appearing\n\nBy the end of the first trimester, most major organ systems have begun developing.\n\n## Common Symptoms\n\nMany people experience:\n\n• Fatigue\n• Nausea\n• Vomiting\n• Breast tenderness\n• Food aversions\n• Frequent urination\n• Mood changes\n• Bloating\n\n## Healthy Habits During The First Trimester\n\n### Prioritize Nutrition\n\nFocus on:\n\n• Fruits\n• Vegetables\n• Whole grains\n• Lean proteins\n• Healthy fats\n\n### Stay Hydrated\n\nAdequate hydration supports both maternal and fetal health.\n\n### Rest When Needed\n\nFatigue is extremely common during early pregnancy.\n\n### Attend Prenatal Appointments\n\nRegular prenatal care helps monitor pregnancy health and development.\n\n## Warning Signs\n\nSeek medical advice if you experience:\n\n• Severe abdominal pain\n• Heavy bleeding\n• Severe dehydration\n• Persistent vomiting\n• High fever\n\n## Emotional Changes\n\nHormonal fluctuations can affect emotions.\n\nExperiencing a range of feelings is normal during this transition.\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Exercise should be completely avoided during pregnancy.\n\nFact: Many people can safely continue appropriate physical activity after consulting a healthcare professional.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nThe first trimester is a period of rapid development and major physical changes. Healthy nutrition, hydration, rest, and prenatal care help support a healthy pregnancy."
  },
  {
    "id": "pregnancy_nutrition_basics",
    "title": "Nutrition During Pregnancy",
    "category": "Pregnancy",
    "readTime": "9 min read",
    "summary": "Learn how healthy nutrition supports pregnancy and discover important nutrients needed for fetal development.",
    "content": "# Nutrition During Pregnancy\n\nNutrition plays a vital role in supporting both the pregnant individual and the developing baby.\n\nA balanced diet provides essential nutrients needed for growth, development, and overall wellbeing.\n\n## Why Nutrition Matters\n\nThe developing baby relies on nutrients from the mother's diet.\n\nHealthy eating supports:\n\n• Brain development\n• Organ development\n• Bone growth\n• Immune system development\n• Maternal energy levels\n\n## Important Nutrients\n\n### Folic Acid\n\nFolic acid supports early brain and spinal cord development.\n\nGood sources include:\n\n• Leafy greens\n• Beans\n• Fortified grains\n\n### Iron\n\nIron helps transport oxygen throughout the body.\n\nSources include:\n\n• Lean meats\n• Lentils\n• Beans\n• Spinach\n\n### Calcium\n\nCalcium supports developing bones and teeth.\n\nSources include:\n\n• Dairy products\n• Fortified plant-based milk\n• Tofu\n• Leafy vegetables\n\n### Protein\n\nProtein supports tissue growth and development.\n\nGood sources include:\n\n• Eggs\n• Fish\n• Poultry\n• Beans\n• Lentils\n\n## Hydration\n\nDrinking enough water helps support:\n\n• Blood circulation\n• Digestion\n• Nutrient delivery\n• Amniotic fluid balance\n\n## Managing Nausea\n\nHelpful strategies may include:\n\n• Eating smaller meals\n• Choosing bland foods\n• Staying hydrated\n• Avoiding strong food odors when possible\n\n## Foods To Limit Or Avoid\n\nRecommendations may vary by country and healthcare provider.\n\nAlways follow guidance from your healthcare team.\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Pregnancy means eating for two.\n\nFact: Pregnancy increases nutritional needs, but quality of food is generally more important than simply eating much larger amounts.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nPregnancy nutrition focuses on providing essential nutrients for both mother and baby. A balanced diet rich in protein, iron, calcium, folate, and fluids supports healthy development."
  },
