  {
    "id": "best_foods_for_pms",
    "title": "Best Foods For PMS",
    "category": "Nutrition",
    "readTime": "8 min read",
    "summary": "Discover how nutrition may help support your body during PMS and learn which foods can help you feel your best before your period.",
    "content": "# Best Foods For PMS\n\nPremenstrual Syndrome (PMS) affects many women during the days leading up to menstruation. Common symptoms may include bloating, mood changes, fatigue, headaches, food cravings, and breast tenderness.\n\nWhile nutrition cannot completely eliminate PMS, a balanced diet may help support overall wellbeing and reduce the impact of some symptoms.\n\n## What Happens During PMS?\n\nPMS occurs during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle, after ovulation and before menstruation begins.\n\nDuring this phase, estrogen and progesterone levels fluctuate. These hormonal changes can affect mood, appetite, energy levels, and fluid balance.\n\n## Magnesium-Rich Foods\n\nMagnesium is an essential mineral involved in muscle function, nerve signaling, and energy production.\n\nSome studies suggest that adequate magnesium intake may help support overall comfort during PMS.\n\nFoods rich in magnesium include:\n\n• Pumpkin seeds\n• Almonds\n• Cashews\n• Spinach\n• Black beans\n• Oats\n• Dark chocolate\n\n## Calcium-Rich Foods\n\nCalcium supports bone health, muscle function, and nerve communication.\n\nGood calcium sources include:\n\n• Milk\n• Yogurt\n• Cheese\n• Fortified plant milks\n• Tofu\n• Leafy green vegetables\n\n## Complex Carbohydrates\n\nComplex carbohydrates provide a steady source of energy and may help maintain stable blood sugar levels.\n\nExamples include:\n\n• Oats\n• Brown rice\n• Quinoa\n• Sweet potatoes\n• Whole grain bread\n\nThese foods may help reduce energy crashes and excessive hunger.\n\n## Fruits And Vegetables\n\nFruits and vegetables provide vitamins, minerals, antioxidants, and fiber.\n\nAim for a colorful variety including:\n\n• Berries\n• Oranges\n• Bananas\n• Broccoli\n• Carrots\n• Leafy greens\n\nBananas are particularly popular during PMS because they contain potassium and vitamin B6.\n\n## Protein For Stable Energy\n\nProtein helps keep you feeling full and supports muscle maintenance.\n\nHealthy protein sources include:\n\n• Eggs\n• Fish\n• Chicken\n• Lentils\n• Chickpeas\n• Greek yogurt\n\n## Staying Hydrated\n\nMany people feel bloated before their period and mistakenly reduce water intake.\n\nIn reality, staying hydrated helps support normal fluid balance and overall health.\n\nCarry a water bottle throughout the day and drink regularly.\n\n## Foods To Enjoy In Moderation\n\nSome people find that limiting certain foods may help them feel better during PMS.\n\nThese include:\n\n• Highly processed foods\n• Excessive sugary snacks\n• Large amounts of caffeine\n• Excessive salt intake\n\nModeration is generally more sustainable than strict restriction.\n\n## A Simple PMS-Friendly Day Of Eating\n\nBreakfast:\n• Oatmeal with berries and nuts\n\nLunch:\n• Grilled chicken, brown rice, and vegetables\n\nSnack:\n• Greek yogurt and fruit\n\nDinner:\n• Salmon, sweet potato, and spinach salad\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Craving chocolate during PMS means your body is unhealthy.\n\nFact: Food cravings are common during PMS. Enjoying treats occasionally as part of a balanced diet is completely normal.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nA PMS-friendly diet focuses on whole foods, protein, fruits, vegetables, hydration, and nutrient-rich foods such as magnesium and calcium sources. Small dietary improvements can help support energy levels, mood, and overall wellbeing throughout the menstrual cycle."
