    "id": "fertile_window_explained",
    "title": "Fertile Window Explained",
    "category": "Fertility",
    "readTime": "8 min read",
    "summary": "Understand what the fertile window is, how long it lasts, and how to identify it during your cycle.",
    "content": "# Fertile Window Explained 🌱\n\nThe fertile window is the period during your menstrual cycle when pregnancy is most likely to occur.\n\nMany people believe they can become pregnant at any time during their cycle. While pregnancy is possible during several days each month, fertility is highest during a specific window around ovulation.\n\n## What Is The Fertile Window?\n\nThe fertile window includes the days leading up to ovulation and the day of ovulation itself.\n\nAn egg survives for approximately 12–24 hours after it is released.\n\nSperm, however, can survive inside the female reproductive tract for up to 5 days under favorable conditions.\n\nBecause sperm can wait for the egg, the fertile window is usually considered to be:\n\n• Five days before ovulation\n• The day of ovulation\n• Up to one day after ovulation\n\n## Why Timing Matters\n\nPregnancy occurs when a sperm fertilizes an egg.\n\nSince the egg survives for a short time, having sperm already present before ovulation increases the chances of fertilization.\n\n## Example Cycle\n\nIf ovulation occurs on Day 14:\n\n• Fertile Window = Days 9–15\n• Highest fertility often occurs during Days 12–14\n\n## Signs You May Be In Your Fertile Window\n\n• Increased cervical mucus\n• Mild pelvic discomfort\n• Increased libido\n• Higher energy levels\n• Positive ovulation predictor test\n\n## Can The Fertile Window Change?\n\nYes.\n\nFactors such as stress, illness, travel, sleep disruption, and hormonal conditions can affect ovulation timing.\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Ovulation always happens on Day 14.\n\nFact: Ovulation varies significantly from person to person and from cycle to cycle.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nThe fertile window is typically the 5 days before ovulation plus the day of ovulation. Understanding this window can help you better understand your reproductive health and fertility."
  },
