    "id": "cervical_mucus_guide",
    "title": "Cervical Mucus Guide",
    "category": "Fertility",
    "readTime": "9 min read",
    "summary": "Discover how cervical mucus changes throughout the menstrual cycle and what these changes may indicate about fertility.",
    "content": "# Cervical Mucus Guide 💧\n\nCervical mucus is a fluid produced by glands in the cervix.\n\nAlthough many people rarely pay attention to it, cervical mucus provides valuable information about hormonal changes and fertility.\n\n## Why Cervical Mucus Matters\n\nCervical mucus helps:\n\n• Protect the reproductive tract\n• Maintain vaginal health\n• Support sperm survival during fertile days\n\nThe appearance and texture of mucus change throughout the menstrual cycle.\n\n## After Your Period\n\nImmediately after menstruation, many people notice:\n\n• Very little mucus\n• Dryness\n\nThese days are generally considered low-fertility days.\n\n## Early Follicular Phase\n\nAs estrogen begins rising:\n\nMucus often becomes:\n\n• Sticky\n• Thick\n• White or cloudy\n\nFertility remains relatively low.\n\n## Approaching Ovulation\n\nAs ovulation approaches, cervical mucus becomes:\n\n• Wet\n• Creamy\n• Smooth\n\nThis indicates increasing fertility.\n\n## Peak Fertility Mucus\n\nNear ovulation, mucus usually becomes:\n\n• Clear\n• Slippery\n• Stretchy\n• Egg-white-like\n\nThis type of mucus helps sperm survive and move more easily.\n\nMany fertility awareness methods consider this the most fertile mucus.\n\n## After Ovulation\n\nProgesterone increases.\n\nMucus often becomes:\n\n• Thick\n• Sticky\n• Minimal\n\nSome people notice very little discharge after ovulation.\n\n## How To Observe Cervical Mucus\n\nYou can observe:\n\n• Appearance\n• Texture\n• Sensation throughout the day\n\nQuestions to ask:\n\n• Does it feel dry?\n• Is it sticky?\n• Is it creamy?\n• Is it slippery and stretchy?\n\n## Factors That May Affect Mucus\n\nChanges may occur due to:\n\n• Hormonal contraceptives\n• Infections\n• Certain medications\n• Hydration status\n• Hormonal conditions\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: All vaginal discharge is a sign of infection.\n\nFact: Normal cervical mucus is a healthy part of the menstrual cycle and changes naturally throughout the month.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nCervical mucus changes throughout the cycle in response to hormones. Egg-white-like mucus typically appears near ovulation and is often considered a sign of peak fertility. Learning to recognize these patterns can help you better understand your cycle."
  },
