    "summary": "Learn what uterine fibroids are, common symptoms, treatment options, and when medical attention may be needed.",
    "content": "# Fibroids Explained 🌸\n\nFibroids are non-cancerous growths that develop in or around the uterus (womb). They are one of the most common gynecological conditions and affect millions of women worldwide.\n\nAlthough fibroids can sound frightening, they are almost always benign (non-cancerous) and many women never realize they have them.\n\n## What Are Fibroids?\n\nFibroids are growths made of muscle and connective tissue.\n\nThey can vary greatly in size:\n\n• As small as a seed\n• As large as a melon\n• Single or multiple growths\n\n## Types Of Fibroids\n\n### Intramural Fibroids\n\nDevelop within the muscular wall of the uterus.\n\nMost common type.\n\n### Subserosal Fibroids\n\nGrow on the outer surface of the uterus.\n\nMay put pressure on nearby organs.\n\n### Submucosal Fibroids\n\nGrow into the uterine cavity.\n\nOften associated with heavy bleeding.\n\n### Pedunculated Fibroids\n\nAttached to the uterus by a stalk-like structure.\n\n## Common Symptoms\n\nMany women have no symptoms.\n\nWhen symptoms occur, they may include:\n\n• Heavy menstrual bleeding\n• Long periods\n• Pelvic pain or pressure\n• Frequent urination\n• Constipation\n• Lower back pain\n• Pain during intercourse\n• Fatigue from blood loss\n\n## Do Fibroids Affect Fertility?\n\nMost women with fibroids can become pregnant.\n\nHowever, certain fibroids—especially submucosal fibroids—may affect fertility or pregnancy outcomes.\n\n## Risk Factors\n\nFactors associated with fibroids include:\n\n• Family history\n• Increasing age during reproductive years\n• Early menstruation\n• Obesity\n• Hormonal influences\n\n## Diagnosis\n\nHealthcare professionals may use:\n\n• Pelvic examination\n• Ultrasound\n• MRI scans\n• Hysteroscopy\n\n## Treatment Options\n\nTreatment depends on symptoms, age, fibroid size, and future pregnancy plans.\n\nOptions may include:\n\n• Monitoring without treatment\n• Hormonal medications\n• Pain management\n• Minimally invasive procedures\n• Surgery in severe cases\n\n## When To Seek Medical Advice\n\nSpeak with a healthcare professional if you experience:\n\n• Very heavy periods\n• Severe pelvic pain\n• Frequent urination\n• Difficulty becoming pregnant\n• Symptoms affecting daily life\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Fibroids always require surgery.\n\nFact: Many fibroids never require treatment and can be safely monitored.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nFibroids are common, non-cancerous uterine growths. While some cause no symptoms, others may lead to heavy bleeding, pelvic discomfort, or fertility challenges. Treatment depends on individual symptoms and needs."
