    "summary": "Understand what adenomyosis is, its symptoms, treatment options, and how it differs from endometriosis.",
    "content": "# Adenomyosis 🩸\n\nAdenomyosis is a condition where tissue similar to the lining of the uterus grows into the muscular wall of the uterus.\n\nThis can cause the uterus to become enlarged and may lead to painful or heavy periods.\n\n## What Happens In Adenomyosis?\n\nNormally, the uterine lining stays inside the uterine cavity.\n\nWith adenomyosis, this tissue grows into the muscle layer of the uterus.\n\nEach month, the tissue responds to hormonal changes and can contribute to inflammation and discomfort.\n\n## Common Symptoms\n\nSymptoms vary from person to person.\n\nCommon symptoms include:\n\n• Heavy menstrual bleeding\n• Severe menstrual cramps\n• Pelvic pain\n• Chronic pelvic pressure\n• Blood clots during periods\n• Pain during intercourse\n\nSome women experience no symptoms.\n\n## Adenomyosis vs Endometriosis\n\nAlthough the names sound similar, they are different conditions.\n\n### Adenomyosis\n\nTissue grows into the uterine muscle.\n\n### Endometriosis\n\nTissue grows outside the uterus.\n\nSome women have both conditions.\n\n## Risk Factors\n\nPossible risk factors include:\n\n• Age 35–50 years\n• Previous pregnancies\n• Previous uterine surgery\n\n## Diagnosis\n\nDiagnosis may involve:\n\n• Medical history\n• Pelvic examination\n• Ultrasound\n• MRI scans\n\n## Treatment Options\n\nTreatment depends on symptoms and reproductive goals.\n\nOptions may include:\n\n• Pain medications\n• Hormonal treatments\n• Intrauterine devices (IUDs)\n• Surgery in severe cases\n\n## When To Seek Medical Advice\n\nConsult a healthcare professional if:\n\n• Period pain is severe\n• Heavy bleeding affects daily life\n• Symptoms worsen over time\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Severe period pain is always normal.\n\nFact: Severe pain may indicate conditions such as adenomyosis or endometriosis and deserves medical evaluation.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nAdenomyosis occurs when uterine lining-like tissue grows into the uterine muscle. It can cause heavy bleeding and painful periods, but effective treatment options are available."
