  "summary": "Consent is the foundation of healthy relationships. Learn what consent means, how it works, and why it matters.",
  "content": "Consent means freely agreeing to participate in an activity. In relationships and sexual situations, consent should always be clear, enthusiastic, informed, and ongoing. Consent is not the absence of a 'no'; it is the presence of a clear 'yes'. Every person has the right to decide what happens to their body. Consent can be given verbally or through clear actions, but communication is always the safest approach.\n\nA person cannot give consent if they are unconscious, asleep, heavily intoxicated, pressured, threatened, manipulated, or under conditions where they do not fully understand what they are agreeing to. Silence does not automatically mean consent.\n\nConsent can also be withdrawn at any time. Someone may feel comfortable with an activity initially and later decide to stop. Respecting boundaries is essential for maintaining trust and safety.\n\nHealthy consent involves honest communication, respect, and mutual understanding. Discussing comfort levels, boundaries, and expectations helps partners feel secure and valued.\n\nRemember: Consent is not a one-time conversation. It is an ongoing process that supports healthy, respectful, and positive relationships."
