  "content": "Sexually transmitted infections (STIs) are infections that can spread through sexual contact. They may be caused by bacteria, viruses, or parasites. Some common STIs include chlamydia, gonorrhea, syphilis, genital herpes, human papillomavirus (HPV), and HIV.\n\nMany STIs cause no symptoms, especially during the early stages. This means a person may have an infection without realizing it. When symptoms do occur, they can include unusual discharge, burning during urination, sores, itching, pelvic pain, or bleeding between periods.\n\nThe most effective ways to reduce STI risk include using protection correctly, limiting exposure to risk factors, getting vaccinated when appropriate (such as HPV vaccination), and having regular health checkups.\n\nRegular STI testing is important because early diagnosis allows treatment and reduces the chance of complications. Untreated infections can sometimes affect fertility, pregnancy outcomes, and long-term reproductive health.\n\nTalking openly with healthcare professionals and partners about sexual health helps create safer relationships and promotes overall wellbeing. Seeking medical advice promptly if symptoms appear is always recommended."
