  "summary": "Understand different birth control options, how they work, and factors to consider when choosing one.",
  "content": "Birth control refers to methods used to prevent pregnancy. Different methods work in different ways, and choosing one depends on personal preferences, medical history, lifestyle, and healthcare guidance.\n\nBarrier methods work by preventing sperm from reaching an egg. These methods can also help reduce the risk of some sexually transmitted infections.\n\nHormonal methods use hormones to prevent ovulation, thicken cervical mucus, or alter the uterine lining. Examples include birth control pills, patches, injections, implants, and hormonal intrauterine devices (IUDs).\n\nLong-acting reversible contraceptives, such as implants and certain IUDs, provide protection for several years and require minimal maintenance.\n\nEmergency contraception may be used after unprotected intercourse to reduce the chance of pregnancy. It works best when taken as soon as possible after the event.\n\nNo birth control method is perfect, and effectiveness can vary depending on consistent and correct use. Consulting a qualified healthcare professional can help determine which option best suits an individual's health needs and goals.\n\nUnderstanding available choices empowers people to make informed decisions about reproductive health and family planning."
